The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and will have a busy schedule.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the Committee who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple’s schedule then includes an interview with the King of Norway Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will peak in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive the award, but only the third to receive the award inside the Committee.
The White House said in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan at the awards ceremony.
The president does not want to avoid this topic because he is aware that he receives this award by being a president who is fighting a war in two countries at the moment.
He stepped up the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to point out.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a cheque of ten million Swedish kroner (approximately 1.1 million euros).
He intends to donate to charities, but he has not yet decided concretely which ones.
His busy schedule will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the King and Queen of Norway, the Head of Government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant at this price at first.
He mentioned, for example, that he felt he did not fully deserve it.
He also repeated several times that this is not a prize for himself alone, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
As soon as the announcement was made, he said it would be an "invitation to action" for him.
