USA: Repetition is Mother of Wisdom
It becomes even comic, the assiduous effort with which Barack Obama, president with a reputation for wisdom, reproduces the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan question, which he considered himself as simple.
When he ended up letting his long-awaited doctrine perspire, it turned out that he had copied it on carbon paper since Bush’s Iraqi scenario three years ago.
Not content to use in the text even several times the expression "like in Iraq", he did not hesitate, moreover, to use the title of Bush's speech of January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements into a civil war-torn Iraq as “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its aftermath.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, emanating from the recommendations of the campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed to such an extent that the newspapers at present do not speak at all about Iraq.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, but, objectively speaking, it left his successor in a much more favorable final situation than could be hoped.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again the campaign commanders who asked him for an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the reluctance of the White House despite the habits of subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but in the absence of a better option, he swindled at least the general of 10,000 soldiers.
It succeeded in removing the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though it originally counted on 10,000.
What brings the most problems to the entire Obama strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete the whole process within three years.
Many doubt that a halving increase will bear the same fruit as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The Afghan situation is marked by the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
In these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders day by day according to what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain nothing more than the eye-powder behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is particularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity on the relationship, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the founding of a "prompt-to-act state", which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy makes him bewildered by his voluntarism.
In the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out of reality heart can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war for their "prompt return home" will bring there a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will regard it as the indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is oriented towards the negative.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the Americans will face the very difficult question of a solution of the problem through the use of military force.
This will have to be answered, for example, at a time when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
Any such solution, however, will lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only ruse for Obama is the fact that he has three years until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to work on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
