Progressive mitigation
Written in the country’s 1978 constitution, China’s one-child policy is unquestionably the most controversial obligation introduced by the communist government to date.
Couples who violate this policy risk huge fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and discrimination in the workplace.
The Chinese authorities have assigned the police a duty to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers have denounced the abuses in implementing this policy.
In rural areas, some officials forced pregnant women with a second child to have an abortion.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to an abnormally high male-to-female ratio.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the policy of the one child.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for city residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases where men and women are already single children -- and in 2007 they softened many of their harsh slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at Beijing University, said central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, posters encouraging families to have only one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who has the right to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
