The United Nations group has draft plans for emission reductions
The U.N.-sponsored climate conference -- so far characterized by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- came back in the spotlight on Friday, due to the release of a document highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas cuts over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations leveraging most of the upcoming time in the charge.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as well as illuminating the way forward.
But it has been seen as an important step forward in time-constrained negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Drafted by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, both in the long term and in the long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and new emerging economies could decrease their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of global temperature rise that policymakers would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN Executive Secretary-General on climate change Yvo de Boer described as “the full picture.”
It shows the guidelines of a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions in 2020, by 25 to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while major developing countries, during the same period, would reduce theirs by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by 50 to 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also restarted negotiations on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impacts of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to prevent deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, U.S. Representative to the Climate Negotiation, rejected any discussion requiring greenhouse gas reductions by industrialized countries, compared to voluntary efforts by major emerging economies, if these were not funded by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is getting tougher on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of major developing countries, Stern said, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his remarks an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said the US chief negotiator either lacked “common sense” or was “extremely irresponsible” for saying earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States arguing over their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers are struggling to find out who should bear the costs of decreasing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold big emitters accountable for their actions.
It’s really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also a Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impacts of climate change have indicated that they will continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say negotiations will at the very least lead to a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission’s climate unit, said the small island states’ action has “put political pressure on the entire political process,” in part because they are now unified and are calling on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The debates became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to solve most of the pending issues before the heads of government reached an agreement.
High-level officials such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister got off their plane and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and information conferences, in order to be able to make claims that will be investigated in the following week.
The real picture of the rally -- in which 13,000 people come and go from the Palais des congrès every day -- guitar-playing activists present night shows mocking countries that they believe betray each other and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than in emails -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
“We are entering the courtyard of greats,” said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy at Conservation International.
The heavy trucks are coming.
