To support his approach, he received the support of MP Hervé de Charette (ex-UMP passed to the NC) who claims ownership of the UDF trademark for having been the first to file it in 2004 at the National Institute of Industrial Property.
But on Friday night, the office of the UDF association, controlled by the friends of François Bayrou who do not intend to be dispossessed, came out of its silence to launch a formal notice to the minister and the deputy, summoning them not to use the acronym anymore and to pass on the property of the brand, under penalty of legal prosecution.
In recent days, you have multiplied the statements indicating that you will propose to your political movement to take back the acronym UDF, writes the association in a letter signed by 19 of the 24 members of the bureau, including François Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez of the MoDem, as well as Senator Jean Arthuis of the Centrist Alliance.
You also thought it good to send on your militant material and on the watch page of your site, the name of this movement, the "New center", the slogan "the UDF of today", also note the signatories of the letter.
As you know, you have no right to use this acronym, explains the office of the UDF which urges the NC to remove "immediately the mention of the name of the UDF from any medium as well as (its) website".
It also asks Hervé de Charette "to transfer ownership of (the) mark to its legitimate successors".
If you did not do so, the courts would be seized to enforce the law and the legitimate rights of UDF members, the signatories warn.
In their letter, they point out that the UDF "has been a political movement in its own right since 1978" and recall that Mr. Morin and his friends "made the choice" to leave in 2007 "to create a competing movement, as others had done in 2002 to create the UMP."
The New Centre therefore, according to them, has no right to use the acronym UDF (Union pour la démocratie française).
They also recall that the last UDF congress voted in 2007 to join the MoDem for three years and the creation of an office responsible for defending "the material and moral interests" of the formation founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
As for Hervé de Charette, the office continues, "when he filed the trademark", he was "no longer a member of the UDF for three years", but at the UMP.
He exploits scandalously and fraudulently the absence of deposit of the acronym UDF to perform it on his behalf.
This indelicacy is turning into a crime, they denounce, before ironizing on the strategy of the NC: "It seems to us that in politics, as in life, it is more worthy to make a name for yourself than to try to get out of anonymity by fraudulently taking a name to which you are not entitled."
Liliane Bettencourt case: François-Marie Banier will be tried for abuse of weakness
The court in Nanterre decided on Friday to try the artist François-Marie Banier in order to determine if, as the daughter of billionaire Liliane Bettencourt accuses him, he took advantage of a state of weakness of the octogenarian to spoliate a part of his fortune.
The 62-year-old photographer, known for his pictures of stars, will be tried on April 15 and 16, 2010 for abuse of weakness, a crime punishable by a maximum sentence of three years in prison and a fine of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>375,000.
This decision means that there will be a trial in this saga-worthy case about one of France’s richest families, in which mother and daughter tear each other apart while holding the reins of the L’Oréal cosmetics empire.
But the 15th correctional chamber also ordered that a medical examination of Liliane Bettencourt, 87, should be conducted collegially by three doctors.
The heiress and main shareholder of L'Oréal has always refused to submit to such an examination, in any case not under the conditions proposed by the Prosecutor's Office of Nanterre during the investigation.
The doctors nominated on Friday will have to submit a report by March 10, 2010 saying in particular if Liliane Bettencourt may have been in a state of weakness and at what periods.
I think she will submit to it.
I'll talk to him about it," Bettencourt's lawyer, Georges Kiejman, said after the hearing.
For his part, Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' lawyer, Olivier Metzner, welcomed the court's decision.
This is excellent news ... The expertise will show that he (Mr. Banier) has manipulated this elderly lady that we must protect, he said.
For the past two years, Liliane Bettencourt's only daughter has filed criminal charges against François-Marie Banier, a photographer and artist who she accuses of taking advantage of her mother's weakness for years to obtain a billion euros in donations, in the form of cheques, life insurance contracts or master paintings.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt has always denied having been manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers a longtime friend.
While the court was due to examine the admissibility of Bettencourt-Meyers' lawsuit, the lawyers' pleadings sometimes turned to the big family unpacking on Friday.
Thus, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer reported three letters sent by her client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, in which she said she was suspicious of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In the letter dated 2003, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "Could you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once, twice a day for fifteen years.
"Françoise, I have never been able to talk to her since her wedding."
For its part, the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office again found that the complainant was inadmissible to act, especially since a guardianship judge refused in recent days to grant her request to open a procedure for judicial protection for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to act in court, she is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one else has to act in his place," said public prosecutor Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
The court ultimately decided that it would rule once the trial had taken place on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers.
Management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees reminds the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of getting employees to adhere to "values" determined from above as it used to be, of imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the business, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering markets back in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preference factors returns regularly!
A demobilization of employees can result in deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emergent part of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, in particular R&D and, even more so, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "demands from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires from employees a commitment that authoritarian management revenues totally contradict.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would be to put the employees at the center of the concerns of the company as well as the customer.
The Relative Usefulness of Internal Opinion Surveys
Will internal opinion polls – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incite this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- Firstly, because I have been able to see that, in the face of a new situation, every structure finally manages, after many detours, to do as a priority... what it has always done.!
- Secondly, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from the major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "levers" (sic) of the commitment of executives, a recent investigation by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr comforts the leaders in a posture of mechanistic governance, unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes adopting a finalistic vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or governance practice, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to realize part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies from the Motivational Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life projects.
By identifying and measuring these mobilizing factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and put their human resources management “in place”.
In this way, they create a basis for the concerted development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: ‘Just War’ Worth Right-Wing Praise to Obama
The US right-wing welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo on Friday, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize winner defended the concept of a "just war" against US enemies.
The Conservatives, who mocked Mr. Obama’s award on October 9, applauded the presidential speech this time, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
“I liked what he said,” Palin, a right-wing Republican, told USA Today, adding that she herself addressed the theme of war “sometimes necessary” in her recently published memoirs.
War is, of course, the last thing I think Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
These terrorists must be stopped there, she said.
Obama, who inherited from his predecessor George W. Bush's two wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked in Oslo on Thursday to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send an additional 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done a "very good job" in Oslo.
I found that the speech was really very good, the former Speaker of the House of Representatives congratulated, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential remarks.
On some sides, I found this speech quite historical, said Mr. Gingrich, who was interviewed on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former president, considered by some to be a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to see "a leftist president" reminding the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not award a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
For Michael Gerson, former pen of George W. Bush reconverted columnist at the Washington Post, Mr. Obama gave "a very American speech".
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world" as "he always does", "he spoke like an American president", reminding Europeans "that they live in a bubble of security that they did not create and that they do not do much to preserve it", Gerson said.
Among the few on the right not to be convinced, a Bush-era hawk, former U.N. Ambassador John Bolton, called the speech "tender, blistered and uninspired" on the National Review Online site.
To the left of the president, Democratic Rep. Dennis Kucinich was alarmed that Barack Obama justified the use of force.
When you wrap war around the notion of justice, you can easily justify the slaughter of innocents, he warned.
The centre-left press, however, remained praiseworthy of the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to believe that the Nobel Prize was awarded prematurely to Mr. Obama, called his speech "superproduction" even for a speaker known for his talent.
Oslo’s speech “should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression,” the California daily said.
Obama "produced the right speech," the New York Times said, deeming it "both dark and uplifting."
Roadrunners: three marathons for a deal that saves Christmas supplies
After three sessions of marathon negotiations, the road sector unions and TLF, the only employers' organization to have remained until the end, reached an agreement on Friday evening that ends the slogan of strike and the threat to Christmas supplies.
During the signing session on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, was "delighted" with this agreement, after several sessions of negotiations, which began Wednesday morning.
After a second night of talks, the negotiators left early on Friday, hoping to sign the agreement text quickly by the end of the morning.
And this even if three employers’ organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had slammed the door.
But it still took more than six hours of a meeting that began at 11 a.m. for everyone to agree and for the text to be signed at 6 p.m.
The conflict "would have been very damaging to business" and "there was a concern that it would disrupt the holidays at the end of the year," Bussereau said.
The text provides for an increase in wages of 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and of 2.9% for the highest (international transport).
In hourly rates, for low wages, "we go from 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It's not much, but we're starting from very far away, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
Either we will give the order to our militants that there are no blockades, no blockades of the supply centers.
But we can always have some recalcitrants who are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of TLF, hailed "a good agreement", although it was "difficult to concede the increases on high wages given the international competition".
According to him, the increases will be of the order of 170 euros per month for the low wages and of 100 to 120 euros for the higher ones.
It is the agreement of common sense and respect for employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) hailed "a historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) referred to "an acceptable compromise".
The agreement also provides for the revaluation of travel costs of 3%, and the general maintenance of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will allow in particular to address the issue of a 13th month and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Mr. Bussereau recalled that "a reduction of 100 million euros in employers' expenses" was the subject of a government amendment to the bill of finance rectification for 2009, voted in the night of Thursday to Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote on it "in identical terms".
The signing of TLF allows the agreement to be applied first to the companies belonging to this organization, and secondly, to the entire profession, in case of extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will be done "as soon as possible," Bussereau said.
Opposition from employers' organizations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "dumb market" because the 100 million euros "had already been promised to the sector to compensate for part of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate urgently, not in conclusion of a shared analysis, but in order not to upset the turkey eaters of the next New Year's Eve, deplored Unostra.
For the Other, the agreement risks "digging the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months".
RER A: disturbances this weekend, unions dissatisfied with RATP proposals
The disturbances on the RER A, France's largest urban transit line, will continue over the weekend, as a meeting on Friday on the second day of a strike between unions and RATP management left them hungry for their premium claim.
