It was then that the management, who had previously refused any discussion during the strike, suggested "in an effort to appease" the meeting.
The conflict threatens to widen to the RER B on Tuesday, after the filing of a notice by Unsa and Independents.
The unions demand a premium of 120 euros (UNSA) to 150 euros including 30 euros variable (CGT, FO, CFDT, South, Independents) and complain about the degradation of working conditions on this line to the daily million travelers.
RER drivers, all in the second part of their career, receive from 2,200 to 2,700 euros gross as well as 600 to 650 euros of bonuses, for shifted schedules, on Sundays and public holidays.
Turkish Justice Dissolves Pro-Kurdish Party, Consequential Decision
The Turkish Constitutional Court on Friday declared the dissolution of the country’s main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by angry protests in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision risks greatly complicating the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community in an attempt to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "focus of activities prejudicial to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," court president Hasim Kiliç told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to pronounce the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's cadres, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party's assets.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MPs would leave parliament rather than sit as unlabeled parliamentarians.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party, however, says it has "no organic ties" to the PKK but refuses to label it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s verdict comes as the government has just reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen their rights, to try to quell Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
DTP leaders had said a breakup could lead to increased tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where numerous protests against the detention conditions of PKK leader Abdullah <0xC3><0x96>calan have escalated into clashes with police in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the large city in the southeast populated mostly by Kurds.
Law enforcement forces fired tear gas grenades and used water cannons, as protesters threw Molotov cocktails or rocks with slingshots.
A hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Türk said the court's decision would "deepen despair".
Turkey cannot solve this issue by banning a party, he told reporters.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of parties.
This does not solve anything, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
This decision is a total torpedo of the democratic openness launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snow can fall.
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a very harsh winter.
But the head of the road clearance and sandblasting service (FES) says that it is not to bother citizens.
This is simply so that the agents can test the technique of the vehicles and learn to master them well.
And according to the astrologers, it could well be for this weekend.
More than 300 officers and 120 vehicles stand ready to tackle snow and ice.
The EDF follows a very elaborate plan here.
Mr. Brauburger explains that as soon as it starts to snow on the city of Frankfurt and the temperatures drop below zero, large sandblasting vehicles travel 20 main routes (called routes A).
This includes high-traffic streets, main thoroughfares, such as the Neue Weg and Hanauer Landstraße.
Also included are fire access, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as Atzelbergstraße.
ESF officers begin their service at three o'clock in the morning.
In case of need, the 1040 kilometers of road must be salted with a road melt that adheres well, in 3 hours maximum time.
This is why the EDF service starts at 3 a.m. "so that the roads are cleared when the daily migration traffic begins".
Where it gets harder, it's when the snow starts falling at 7:30 in the morning.
This poses problems, the head of the road clearance and sandblasting service tells us "because no motorist is willing to let the salting vehicles pass".
Then, if it does not snow anymore, we take care of access roads and service roads - such as the Rat-Beil-Straße.
Secondary roads and side streets come last.
Mr. Brauburger knows well that this always causes some complaints.
At five o'clock in the morning, the FES foot team sets off to clear out areas deemed dangerous and crossings.
As far as cycling paths are concerned, EDF services are generally unable to deal with them.
Mr Brauburger said there was a special service in Frankfurt which monitored the condition of the bridges between 10 p.m. and 4.30 a.m.
As ice forms very quickly on these surfaces, salting vehicles intervene as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
There are also times when the police call on this special service for snacks in need.
The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long by 1.50 meters high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues report in Thursday’s Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological features.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the lands emerging from the supercontinent, the Pangea, and was near the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the kinship ties, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists, at the site of Gohst Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team recounts that they sometimes found a dozen bones in one day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Triassic.
Scientists quickly realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations have uncovered the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories regarding the beginnings of dinosaur evolution.
Researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontologists share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn doesn't think this discovery is particularly spectacular, but he says it confirms some theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
However, most of the earliest fossils are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the earliest dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the saurians were divided into three major evolutionary groups: the theropods (carnivores) which include the later emerged tyrannosaur and velociraptor and from which birds descend, the sauropods, quadrupeds at the long neck, and those related to them and the herbivores such as the ornithistoschial species that are part of them.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa was one of the first theropods.
This species presents an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues that the Tawa hallae possessed small air sacs in its bones at the level of the skull, just like birds that are descendants of theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
As the related lineage of the huge sauropods also possessed air sacs and a light frame, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three major lines of evolution split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is, all the lands that formed the Pangean supercontinent.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot be descended from a common ancestor that migrated, the researchers said.
Alan Turner of the Natural History Museum in New York and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a palaeontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the silesaur, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a misconception because there are in South America a large number of dinosaur fossils that have been preserved while practically none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread across the planet, fostering the development of many new species, while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and Jurassic.
Such a success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction that dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or else, the dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favored the flowering of a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and that since that time was vegetating in the shadows: it was mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are those of professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley in California.
There are those of lecturers from the University of Naples, Quebec City, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
The police evacuation of the casino of J.W. Goethe University in Frankfurt is making waves all over the planet.
278 professors and teachers from J.W. Goethe University, as well as other higher education institutions in Germany, Europe and North and South America, express their solidarity with the protest students of the Westend Campus.
In a statement written in German and English they condemned the police intervention demanded by the university's steering committee.
Last week, University President Werner Müller-Estler had buildings occupied by students and teachers on strike evacuated after walls and works of art were smeared with graffiti.
Five students were injured during the evacuation.
The signatories consider that the degradation did not justify "such a violent intervention by the police commando against students and teachers who had organized their own classes".
The evacuation represents an "unacceptable attack" on freedom of research and teaching.
Focusing attention exclusively on acts of vandalism serves only to "delegitimize and criminalize the protest" and attempts to make the reasons for the mobilization forgotten.
The steering committee of the University thus avoided the debates which would nevertheless be indispensable.
The judges demanded that the criminal prosecution be immediately suspended.
The majority of the occupants did not take part in the degradations.
Legitimation of protests
The young people of the Verdi trade union in the service sector and the German Trade Union Confederation (DGB) show solidarity with the students.
The protests are just a legitimate expression of growing concern for our own future, says Verdi regional youth secretary Alexander Klein.
As for the Minister of Science of the Land of Hesse Eva Kühne-Hörmann (CDU), she took part in the action taken by the President of the University and the police.
We thank the President of the University.
Any occupation and degradation of the site is totally unacceptable, she told the Wiesbaden Regional Parliament last Thursday on the TV show Aktuelle Stunde.
We understand the meaning of the protests but do not accept vandalism, said CDU member of the regional parliament Peter Beuth.
The opposition SPD parliamentary groups, the Greens and the Left (die Linke) did not share this view.
The CSU takes the pretext of some painted walls to criminalize the protests, said Janine Wissler of the Left Party (Linke)
Instead of thinking about the students’ arguments and demands, we evacuate them.
The Left party has tabled a motion that summons the Minister of the Interior to submit a report on the conditions of the police intervention.
The new Silicon-Valley
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a place of search for secret armaments, under strict surveillance.
Today with its 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the center of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the Soviet "Silicon Valley".
Important production and research sites in micro- and nanoelectronics are located there.
As early as September 2008, representatives from Zelenograd established links with Riedberg, the Frankfurt science centre – with the academic institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives from Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a "Protocol of close collaboration".
The signatories were Deputy Mayor of Moscow Yuri Rosljak and Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz Head of Project Section for Frankfurt.
In 2010 representatives of FIZ and SMEs, whose strong point is scientific research, will leave for Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
This is a sustainable scientific exchange.
