The Worlds of Dreams
Some see, all awake, images and hear voices that no one else sees or hears.
It is not only in psychic patients, or under the influence of drugs, that the limits between imagination and reality are blurred.
As long as these phenomena manifest themselves during sleep, everything is fine.
When we are lying in our darkened rooms, we can unfetteredly indulge in the wildest dreams and fantasies.
However, one who, awake, experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, soon has the reputation in our Western world of being crazy or drugged, or at least of being an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in psychic patients or under the effect of drugs.
It is our imagination that is at stake: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, but that sometimes incites the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to merge.
A state of conscious awakening, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, in the best of cases it is called visions, in the worst of madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance, neurotransmitter substances of the brain - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and achetylcholine - breaks down and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts often occur during schizophrenic psychosis.
The earthly force of attraction no longer has power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between madness and dreaming.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of dream-awakening; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 "a great resemblance between madness and dream", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, deliriums and sensory illusions that compose it".
We are in the fall of 2001 when Henning T turns into a comic book character.
Its body is in two dimensions with crisp colors.
The earthly attraction no longer has power over him, he hovers at the edge of the ceiling.
He feels a blow.
Behind him winged devil creatures, grinning, their mouths bloody, showing their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels pain all over his body.
Thundering, evil voices, screaming, coming out of the walls and the radio.
He can no longer bear those voices that insult and humiliate him.
Henning T. pulls two cables from his stereo, actually a loop, and attaches it to a hook attached to the ceiling.
He climbs on a baffle and passes the loop around his neck.
He's jumping.
The loop comes off.
Let it serve as a lesson for you, shout the voices in a choir to tear out his eardrum. "Go to a clinic and get yourself treated!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has lived through six acute psychoses, the last two years, the first nearly 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: schizo-affective psychosis, paranoid, in addition he is manic-depressive, he takes medications for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
During the psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep despair.
Illusions are a cruel reality.
About one percent of the population suffers at least once in their lifetime from schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is the most common disease after depression.
In a schizophrenia crisis, people can no longer tell the difference between the inner world and the outer world, they find themselves in a state of hyperexcitation, which causes them to suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relational madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon either.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter the disturbing signals, the conscious is drowned under the sensations.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the locks to a tide of ideas and fantasies from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the department of psychiatry at the Heidelberg University Hospital (Allgemeine Psychiatrie im Universitätsklinikum).
Schizophrenia is in the middle of the situation, all with a meaning centered on it.
At the same time he finds himself in a passive role, he is like in a dream, overcome by events and cannot act on them actively.
This is why people with schizophrenia often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
In general they do not have the possibility to adjust reality, illusions are a cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Experience a hallucination once in a lifetime.
Unlike the dream, according to Fuchs, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is perceived during psychosis is fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the lived takes place in a real setting.
Why our brains make this kind of cabrioles, is still a puzzle for researchers.
Exceptional situations can cause anyone to momentarily lose perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people will develop psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
The researchers assume that the affected people have tiny brain damage.
It is assumed that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But what remains unexplained is the way in which the anomaly of the neural system occurs and furthermore the fact that it does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger for psychosis, if there is a predisposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses because they act on neurotransmitters.
When our brain heats up.
What is crazy, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck, is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them while others buy drugs very expensive to get them.
The pleasant or unpleasant perception of illusions is often just a matter of point of view.
For the past ten years, Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and illusory image phenomena: last year he published his findings in a book entitled "The Unreal World in Our Heads".
Hallucinations are well part of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychoses but also of an impressive number of other pathologies.
These include psychic disorders such as borderline or depression but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or head trauma.
It is surprising that under certain conditions even the brains of healthy people are prone to hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that process sensory perceptions are hyperactive or not sufficiently restrained; when our brain heats up but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like a brain injury or psychosis.
But also lack of stimulus, stress, love grief or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, a third of participants admit to having experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In summer 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and she goes to high school.
A girl who can do anything normal, really.
If there were no images and voices.
During recreation, it happens that a young boy, thin, with long brown hair, speaks to him.
When she answers her comrades look at her, astonished – no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think that this shy girl is a lunatic dreamer but Sarah K does not dream, she is sure.
She is awake, hears and sees this boy just as she sees and hears the girl sitting next to her on the bench.
She can even feel his presence momentarily.
It's a nice feeling, she finds this young man sympathetic.
Am I crazy? she asks herself sometimes.
But she knows well that this young man and the other visions are not real and that they will disappear again.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
Visions are often heavy.
When she's in class, sometimes she can't take the class because the teacher is just presenting a new student in her eyes and ears while he's invisible to others and the teacher is visibly explaining equations to the board.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
When, in the darkness of her room, she waits for the sleep that comes too seldom and too late, she often cannot distinguish whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the images she sees, the smiling faces or the girl with bloody cuts on her arms and legs are in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, she cries out to these creatures.
She doesn't tell her parents or friends about it, they'd think she was crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She got her bachelor's degree last year and she lives with her friend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she came into contact with psychologist Kasten over the internet, she knows very well that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough stimulation, the likelihood is high that they will have hallucinations after a while.
I guess the brain isn't busy enough, so there's animation.
Sarah K., an only daughter, was afraid of other children when she was little and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at age 13 that the man she called daddy, since she was of age to think, was not her real father.
These are the same brain areas that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for real impressions and noises, so it is very difficult for people like Sarah K to tell the difference between illusion and reality. "Every experiment," according to Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is formed from there.
Hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real.”
For Kasten, night dreams are also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
That’s why Kasten advises her patients to cherish hallucinations as a special talent.
There is only one step between dreaming and hallucination.
In our overly consciousness-centered world, it is unfortunate that we soon tend to take imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, a professor in Heidelberg and chief physician at the clinic of psychiatry and psychotherapy at Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease but it also contains something positive, something creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oniroid form of experience, a particular form of the modification of awakened consciousness by dreaming.
Oniroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is awake.
The oniroid state of consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies such as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully conscious, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that affects his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dreaming and hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in an intolerable situation in itself, an organizational capacity that is given to us men, so as not to sink into the void of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his oniroid experiences in his book "Change of heart" as a safeguarding action of the soul.
He is 49 years old, at the moment when his conscious leaves for a journey of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; during this time, his body is condemned to remain immobile in resuscitation.
Claussen immerses himself in a world he created from scratch, visits foreign places, travels back in time . He sees himself as an old man lying in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages among nobles who manufacture narcotics based on blood.
He is kidnapped by a Greek on a motorcycle that takes him to his country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the snowy Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
He absorbs himself completely into this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes describing what he experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental travel are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
We can even say that they are much more distinct and more intensive than the actual experience.
The intensity of this experience explodes the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, oniroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even when we are awake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, "can cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be very enriching.
