75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generation who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fecundity and professional career of women in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no room for doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers have had their careers limited due to motherhood.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether the woman works or not and the type of job she has.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unsteady job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, postpone entering life as a couple and early pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in as a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 for those working in the public sector. "These data show that women with a stable job needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to push back the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised greatly influences maternity, but less the date of beginning of common life,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the age gap between women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the later they get married and have their first child.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35- to 49-year-old group, those who completed elementary and higher education were first-time mothers at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
"Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education get married and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child, "said Delgado.
