Michelin said that this campaign is in line with its commitment to road safety, which “goes beyond the design and manufacture of increasingly safe products” and affirmed that it contributes to this objective through other educational and informative actions.
This new campaign to encourage the use of two-wheeled helmets, under the motto "To be or not to be", will include a first phase during which posters will be distributed in more than 500 motorcycle garages, to ensure the widest dissemination.
Finally, Michelin stressed that road safety “is a constant concern” for the company, because as a manufacturer of tyres for two-wheeled vehicles, one of its main objectives is to develop increasingly safer products.
Sales of light commercial vehicles are increasing
After almost two years, the light commercial vehicle market is starting to see some light at the end of the tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in November in Spain represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, they represent the first increase after 22 consecutive months of decrease, according to figures from the union of manufacturers Anfac and Ganvam, that of dealers.
The good news, however, is that the reference for the comparison in November 2008 was particularly poor, with a decrease of 60% compared to the previous year.
As a result, despite the rebound last month, registrations accumulated during these 11 months are 40% below those of the previous year.
Since January, 95,853 vehicles that fall into the light commercial vehicle category (passenger cars, pick-up trucks, vans, light vans and light trucks) have been sold.
The large clouds that most affect their demand have not dissipated, because although they are also purchased by individuals, most purchases are made by small or medium-sized companies, which pay in almost 100% of the cases through external financing.
Thus, in addition to the constraints implied by the limitation of bank loans, other factors must be added such as the increase in the unemployment rate or the persistence of the bad economic situation.
In view of this situation and unlike passenger vehicles, the aid for the purchase of the 2000E was of little use.
In addition to individuals, freelancers and SMEs who want to acquire a light commercial vehicle of less than 3.5 tonnes with a CO2 emission level that does not exceed 160 grams per kilometer, can also benefit, but the number of operations speaks for itself.
Yesterday, at Ganvam, the need for the administration to pay special attention to these vehicles and also to industrial vehicles (trucks and buses) was reiterated.
The dealership association forecasts a year 2010 similar to the one that is ending, for which it calculates a drop in sales (of passenger vehicles and 4x4) of 19%.
Emergency braking aid is now compulsory
As has been the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as will be the case with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a deficiency period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, although, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The Emergency Brake Assist acts by increasing the brake pressure in an emergency detected by the system thanks to the kick given by the driver.
But the latter does not always maintain the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by car component manufacturer Bosch, one-third of drivers involved in an accident were unable to brake before the collision, and half of them did not take full advantage of its strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in revenge, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance that the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of element, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four accidents with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to a radar or a camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum force on the brakes to minimize damage.
