After rosy days since last spring, during which asset inflation was the dominant note in the markets, uncertainty is emerging again, which is not surprising since it is their natural state, in an environment where agents make decisions about a future by nature uncertain.
The remedy used by central banks to stabilize markets has been to monetize debt through the direct purchase of assets and indirectly by giving abundant liquidity at near-zero rates, so that financial institutions buy assets to mobilise.
Central banks have already confirmed that direct asset purchases have been practically finalized and, without questioning their non-conformist liquidity policy, are starting to put a bit of sand in the gears, as the ECB has done, with their one-year auction next week.
Therefore, investors doubt the ability of the global economy to maintain economic recovery without heterodox measures and we are witnessing a reversal of the reduction in risk premiums.
Stock market volatility and corporate bond spreads are increasing again, although they remain very far from the paranormal levels they reached at the beginning of the year.
States have been forced to socialize private risk and public debt is again affected.
There is once again a flight towards quality and the US, Japan and Germany have been the havens chosen by investors, causing an increase in the differences between the eurozone countries and Germany.
Spain was hardly affected by this episode of instability, but then Standard & Poor's threatened a further downward revision of the qualification of the Kingdom of Spain.
