CNMV authorizes Paternina exclusion bid submitted by Inversora Mer
The National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) yesterday authorized the exclusion bid presented by Inversora Mer on Federico Paternina on October 9.
The oversight body explained that it authorized this operation because it understood that its terms were in line with current standards and that it considered the content of the explanatory leaflet presented, following the amendments applied on December 2nd, to be "sufficient".
The CNMV has specified that the offer concerns the acquisition of 550,008 shares of Federico Paternina at a price of 7.65 euros per share, which represents 8.95% of the share capital, composed of 6,142,786 shares admitted to trading on the Madrid and Bilbao stock exchanges.
He further explained that 5,592,778 million shares had been immobilized, and could not in any way be transferred before the finalization of the offer, which he indicated that the price had been set by Federico Paternina, in accordance with the provisions of the standards in force.
New tools for car expertise
In these days of bad weather and accidents, car garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have suffered a loss are brought back to a garage, where an expert must assess the damage suffered and the cost of repair.
Each claim is different, and calculating the cost of parts and labor time can be a long and complex job.
Calculating by hand the cost of a repair between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>20,000 and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30,000, including parts and labor can take two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the assistance of the most recent computer tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
This is why almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
Providers of claims assessment and maintenance services and solutions focus on collecting information provided by manufacturers, then processing it and offering it to their customers in the form of a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the North American group Solera, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
The other companies competing in the field of assessment tools and the development of information on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with data provided by manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, the company in Spain with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, so that in the last five years, more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the previous fifteen years.
When a new car comes on the market, these companies get to work.
This is very hard work, because you have to catalog each of the thousand parts of the vehicle and enter its price.
In addition, a "smart" graphical image of each model is created on which the different parts of a passenger car can be clicked.
If it is a massively sold model, the job can be ready in a week if the process progresses very quickly.
If it is a low-selling car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of the cars marketed in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, they have for example information about Porsches, but not Ferraris or Lamborghinis.
For vehicles on the road, the figure exceeds 99%.
To carry out the work of documentation and development of databases, Audatex has eight centers throughout the world (in Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them specializes in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than one hundred technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>90 million each year to develop these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million data is recorded, and customers receive updates every other day.
The development of this huge flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and offer varied products.
The most common application concerns repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing breakage parts or for calculating the market value or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer it in our country, but it does in the United States.
From the products offered by Audatex, it is easy to get an idea of the type of support it can provide to professionals in the sector.
This company offers ten different tools, the flagship product being AudaPlus, the standard solution for claims assessment, for experts.
It includes cars, motorcycles, light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it takes into account the estimated repair times by the manufacturer or the paint scales.
This tool is purchased according to its use, for each estimate.
The highest cost is 5.75 euros, for customers who use it little, up to ten times a month.
Then, each insurance company, which carries out thousands of expertises, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the total identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it came off the assembly line, only thanks to its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle lenses, and AudaSubastas is a server open to the professional sector on the Internet that allows bidding on vehicles declared wreckage.
Its statistics service is very useful to identify trends, perform geo-demographic analyses or know common problems by brand or model.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a given brand went to the garage for a breakdown or how many suffered serious losses for a given period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tools.
It markets, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for experts and provides digital images, as well as access to the manufacturer's official parts, prices and times.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, founded in 1971, as a provider of services and solutions for claims assessment, breakdowns or car maintenance.
The GT Evaluation Guide is a historical reference product in the market.
The company works with 24,000 users in garages, 3,100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Its turnover has increased at a rate of 20% per annum over the past three years, and it generated a turnover of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>10.8 million in 2008.
At the beginning of last year, she undertook her internationalization process, with the establishment of an office in Paris.
For its part, Audatex was born in Germany in 1966 and settled in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its turnover is made in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. It works with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 garages, of which 3,000 are located in Spain.
The global turnover of the Solera Group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) will be $557 million, 3.3% more than in 2008.
In our country, the company will receive 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than last year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was listed on the stock exchange for $1 billion, today its shares are valued at a total of $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, it has been listed on the New York Stock Exchange and is part of the Standard & Poor's benchmark index.
Internet Auction of Accidented Cars
Last October, the Solera Group bought Autoonline, an Internet platform for the sale of cars, motorcycles and special vehicles.
The transaction involved a cost of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>59.5 million for 85% of the company's capital, which could expand next year to the remaining 15%.
The objective of the acquisition was to offer more value-added services to its customers, with the possibility of accessing a huge international market.
This estimation and sales service is exclusively aimed at professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, garages, brokers and professional sellers who must be registered before starting to carry out operations.
This platform was established in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650,000 operations across Europe, including 500,000 in Germany.
Among its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
There are currently more than 1500 sellers and 4000 experts registered on the site.
It manages 3,000 ads per day and on the Spanish market, 100 new ads are published every day.
According to Spanish law, a car whose chassis number has been removed can no longer drive, but on the other hand, some parts that are not damaged can be used as spare parts.
Collectible cars can be re-registered, although they have been removed, after complex procedures.
Garage quotation in four steps
With the Auda-Taller tool, the Audatex company guarantees that the user gets a quote in just four steps: identify the vehicle, find the spare part, create a quote and generate it.
Ease of use is an essential element of these systems, especially to convince older professionals who, to a greater or lesser extent, are reluctant to use new management techniques.
The database includes 1,034 vehicles, including 666 passenger cars, 109 off-road vehicles, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Naturally, to use it, a computer and an Internet connection are necessary.
Once the model to be repaired is identified by its chassis number, an actual graphic image of the model in question appears and the necessary part is selected.
The user can include variables such as labor price, surcharges or discounts, and then print the quote to hand over to the customer.
AudaTaller is not an estimation tool like AudaPlus, but a catalogue of references.
The main difference between these two systems is that the garage system does not include the estimated labour time.
The cost of using this tool for the garage is 350 euros per year, which can be credited.
Currently, the Audatex company is working to make these images in three dimensions.
This is an innovation that mechanics see with a very good eye, since it will allow, for example, to select a door and rotate it to see the inner face.
